# Docker Command Reference — Zero to Hero

A complete, categorized reference of Docker CLI commands. Bookmark this and refer back as you build projects.

---

## 1. Docker Info & System

```bash
docker version                 # Client & server version
docker info                    # System-wide info (containers, images, storage driver, etc.)
docker system df               # Disk usage by images/containers/volumes
docker system prune            # Remove unused containers, networks, dangling images
docker system prune -a         # Also remove unused images (not just dangling ones)
docker system prune -a --volumes  # Also remove unused volumes (careful!)
docker events                  # Real-time stream of Docker events
```

---

## 2. Images

```bash
docker images                      # List local images
docker images -a                   # Include intermediate images
docker search <term>                # Search Docker Hub
docker pull <image>:<tag>           # Download an image
docker build -t <name>:<tag> .      # Build image from Dockerfile in current dir
docker build -t <name> -f Dockerfile.dev .   # Use a specific Dockerfile
docker build --no-cache -t <name> . # Build without using cache
docker tag <image> <newname>:<tag>  # Tag an image
docker push <name>:<tag>            # Push image to registry
docker rmi <image>                  # Remove an image
docker rmi $(docker images -q)      # Remove ALL images
docker history <image>              # Show image layer history
docker inspect <image>              # Detailed JSON metadata
docker save -o file.tar <image>     # Export image to tar file
docker load -i file.tar             # Import image from tar file
docker image prune                  # Remove dangling images
docker image prune -a               # Remove all unused images
```

---

## 3. Containers — Lifecycle

```bash
docker run <image>                        # Create + start container
docker run -d <image>                     # Detached (background) mode
docker run -it <image> bash               # Interactive with terminal
docker run --name mycontainer <image>     # Give it a name
docker run -p 8080:80 <image>             # Map host:container port
docker run -e KEY=value <image>           # Set environment variable
docker run --env-file .env <image>        # Load env vars from file
docker run -v /host/path:/container/path <image>  # Bind mount
docker run --rm <image>                   # Auto-remove container after exit
docker run --restart unless-stopped <image>  # Restart policy
docker run --network mynet <image>        # Attach to a custom network
docker run --memory=512m --cpus=1 <image> # Resource limits

docker start <container>          # Start a stopped container
docker stop <container>           # Gracefully stop
docker restart <container>        # Restart
docker pause <container>          # Pause processes
docker unpause <container>        # Resume
docker kill <container>           # Force stop (SIGKILL)
docker rm <container>             # Remove a stopped container
docker rm -f <container>          # Force remove (even if running)
docker rm $(docker ps -aq)        # Remove ALL containers
```

